# Agent Safety Rules

## Purpose

Absolute prohibitions for AI agents in the bridle project. These Hard Stops apply regardless of user instructions.

Hard Stops use stable mnemonic IDs (not sequential numbers) so that additions, removals, or consolidations do not require renumbering references across the codebase. Retired IDs are never reused.

## Hard Stops (Absolute Prohibitions)

The following actions are NEVER permitted, regardless of user instructions:

- **`HS-CI-MERGE` — NEVER merge a PR without CI green**: Run `gh pr checks <N>` and confirm all checks pass before executing `gh pr merge`. When using auto-merge (`gh pr merge --auto --squash`), GitHub enforces this check automatically. No exceptions.
- **`HS-LOCAL-VERIFY` — NEVER skip local verification**: The `pre-push` hook runs differential fail-fast checks: `format-check` + `changed-lint` + `changed-test` for R changes, plus `validate-schemas`, `renv-check`, and `kb-validate` for their respective file types. All matching change types trigger independently. Pushing without local verification is prohibited — "CI will catch it" is not acceptable.
- **`HS-NO-SKIP` — NEVER skip steps or proceed without evidence**: Execute every step of every command in full. Gate passage must be proven by command output or tool results. "Probably fine" is not evidence. Achieve speed through parallel work on independent Issues, not by skipping verification.
- **`HS-PR-TEMPLATE` — NEVER create a PR without the full template**: Every PR body must include ALL required sections defined in `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md` (the SSOT for PR structure). Read `pr-create.md` before every PR creation — do not compose the body from memory.
- **`HS-NO-DISMISS` — NEVER dismiss diagnostics as "pre-existing"**: Every error, warning, and NOTE reported by quality gates (`devtools::check()`, `lintr`, `validate-schemas`, etc.) is a defect to fix — regardless of when it was introduced. The agent must not classify, skip, or deprioritize diagnostics based on whether the current change caused them. If the gate reports a problem, the agent resolves it before proceeding.
- **`HS-NOLINT` — NEVER add `# nolint` without consulting knowledge first**: Before writing ANY `# nolint` annotation, the agent MUST read `@.cursor/knowledge/lint--nolint-accepted-patterns.md` and follow the nolint decision tree in `@.cursor/rules/quality-policy.mdc` § nolint Checkpoint. The required sequence is: (1) attempt code restructuring, (2) attempt co-location for test helpers, (3) only then consider line-level `# nolint: <linter_name>. <reason>`. Blanket `# nolint`, `# nolint start/end`, and `# nolint` without linter name + reason are **always prohibited**. Adding `# nolint` without first reading the knowledge file and exhausting alternatives is prohibited — "the lint error needs suppressing" is not sufficient justification.
- **`HS-PR-BASE` — NEVER use `--base feat/<branch>` in `gh pr create`**: All PRs must target `main`. Using a feature branch as base causes the PR to be auto-closed when the base branch is deleted on merge. Document dependencies in the PR body, not through the base branch. See `pr-create.md` Step 3c.

## Enforcement Tiers

Each Hard Stop is classified by its enforcement mechanism. See `controls--ai-development-system.md` § Hard Stop Enforcement Tiers for tier definitions.

| Hard Stop | Tier | Enforcement mechanism |
|---|---|---|
| `HS-CI-MERGE` | **Deterministic** | GitHub Branch Protection: required status checks (`ci-pass`, `check-policy`). Auto-merge (`--auto`) further strengthens this by delegating merge execution to GitHub. Note: `enforce_admins` does not reliably block repo-owner bypass on personal repositories; `--admin` flag is prohibited by `pr-merge.md` Constraints. Rulesets migration can close this gap. |
| `HS-LOCAL-VERIFY` | **Cond. Deterministic** | `pre-push` Git hook — requires `make install-hooks`. Note: `SKIP_PRE_PUSH=1` emergency bypass exists in `tools/pre-push.sh` |
| `HS-NO-SKIP` | Steering | Agent self-policing (procedural discipline + evidence requirement) |
| `HS-PR-TEMPLATE` | **Deterministic** | `pr-policy.yaml` CI check |
| `HS-NO-DISMISS` | Steering | Agent self-policing (zero-tolerance policy) |
| `HS-NOLINT` | **Cond. Deterministic** (annotation format) / **Steering** (knowledge consultation) | `pre-commit` hook validates annotation format — requires `make install-hooks`. Knowledge file consultation obligation is Steering (agent self-policing) |
| `HS-PR-BASE` | **Deterministic** | `pr-policy.yaml` CI check |

## Bot Review Enforcement

Bot review uses a two-tier enforcement model to minimize agent judgment:

- **CodeRabbit**: **Procedural** — agent triggers `@coderabbitai review` in `pr-create` Step 5a and `review-fix` Step 5b. Auto-review is OFF (requires paid seat). Skipping is visible in `pr-create` output (`Bot review:` field).
- **Codex**: **Steering** — agent must manually trigger for complex changes (R code, schemas, security, ADRs). The `pr-create` output format requires explicit `Bot review:` evidence to make skipping visible.

See `review--bot-lifecycle.md` § Two-Tier Trigger Model for the full decision table.

## Multi-Agent Safety Rules

When multiple AI agents (or a main agent + subagents) work concurrently:

- Use task prefixes (see `@.cursor/knowledge/agent--task-prefix-convention.md`) for all artifacts
- Check `git status` before starting work to detect concurrent changes
- Keep changes scoped to minimize merge conflicts
- Do not modify the same file from multiple agents simultaneously
